{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"85ad9c0d-45f6-4d87-8b17-b7976b2b889b","content":"No repo-specific docs found. Here's the general guidance for macOS:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS defaults to `/cores/`):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Run your NativeAOT app** — when it crashes, macOS will write a Mach-O core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **Check for Apple crash reports** in:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   \n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces automatically.\n\n5. **Analyze the core dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./YourApp\n   ```\n\n6. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check:\n   - SIP (System Integrity Protection) may block core dumps for signed binaries.\n   - The app's entitlements — you may need `com.apple.security.get-task-allow`.\n   - Disk space — core files can be large.\n\n> **Tip:** On macOS 12+, `kern.coredump` must be `1` (`sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1`). For NativeAOT specifically, the crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is often the quickest path to a usable stack trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b4627571-6ea4-43d3-a9b8-495e00303c6a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository is empty, so there's no repo-specific documentation to reference. I'll answer from general knowledge about macOS crash dumps for NativeAOT apps.","outputTokens":439},"id":"ac06b1a7-6072-4475-bef2-813c129925d6","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:05:21.172Z","parentId":"8d37926d-15b3-487a-85e1-fd4a2de50039"}
